  "prompt": "Does every dog has rabies?",
  "response": "No, not every dog has rabies. Rabies is a viral disease that can affect mammals, including dogs, but it is not present in all dogs. The disease is transmitted through the bite of an infected animal. Vaccination against rabies is common and is often mandated by law in many places, which helps to control the spread of the virus. A healthy and vaccinated dog is not likely to have rabies. However, if a dog is bitten by a rabid animal or has not been vaccinated, there is a risk of rabies infection. Regular vaccination and monitoring of pets help prevent the spread of this disease.",
